<br>
She wondered if she should tell Stormygale what Valtathien had told her in their most recent meetings or whether it would just upset her unnecessarily.  After all, Athene didn’t know how much of what Valt said was true.  The conversations with Stormygale’s father had been protracted and confusing—and mesmerizing—spanning years of history, some of which was new to Athene entirely.  Much of it—the business about Stormygale’s grandfather, for instance—simply defied credibility; and Athene wondered if Valtathien had, in fact, simply lost his hold on reality.  Saphron would likely vouch for that. <br>
<br>
Regardless, Athene was worried or vaguely uneasy.  Whether or not Belthezius had been reborn in a guise very like his son’s, there was the still unresolved matter of the necromancer who had haunted Abruzi’s last days.  Who had that necromancer been, and what had led him to Abruzi?  Could Valtathien’s father actually be searching for Stormygale for the nefarious reason his son had suggested?  <br>
<br>
Perhaps the matter of the locket and Valt’s warnings were not something Athene should attempt to judge herself.  Stormygale was a grown woman, and she was now sufficiently recovered to participate in any discussions regarding her own past … and present.<br>
<br>
Athene would go to Stormygale and lay the entire complicated story before her.  Let Stormy decide what to do with the information.<br>
<br>
That decision made, Athene felt immensely relieved.  She ended her anxious pacing and set her feet toward a goal.  If Stormy were awake, they could speak without further delay.<br>
<br>
