<br>
Saphron said nothing for the moment, but it was clear from the set of her hands on her hips that she was displeased.  “Besides,” Athene said, “she’s Claw … or probably will be.”<br>
<br>
Saphron’s eyes widened, and a look of vague recognition flickered across her face.  “She is?”  Then her eyes narrowed, and she addressed the woman.  “Kandiya Holytears, you said?”<br>
<br>
The young woman nodded quickly, her eyes darting from face to face. Either she was truly terrified of something, or she was a consummate actress.  Athene, who did not share Saphron’s innate distrust of the Teir’dal, did not believe she was acting. “Her name is listed among the guild applicants on the public recruiting board outside the guild hall,&quot; Athene said quietly. &quot;Of course, there are many names there, but I remember hers.  She’s a cleric.” <br>
<br>
Saphron, who had had less time to interest herself in guild affairs during the days of Stormygale’s convalescence, was interested now and a bit less distrustful—but only a bit.  The bid to join the Claw could be a ruse to gain access and information.  She and Stormygale exchanged a meaningful look.  Stormygale was fiercely loyal to her guild.  If Kandiya were not honorable in intentions, she would bear the brunt of a Stormygale-led, public relations nightmare that would haunt her the rest of her days.<br>
<br>
“Let’s go, Ladies!” said Stormygale, her mind made up. “Quickly!”  <br>
<br>
The air around the three pulsed with energy as Stormygale’s spell illuminated the stall with a crackling flash of light.  Athene felt gravity give way as the portal opened.<br>
<br>
Then the three disappeared from view.<br>
